Ok whatev, OP here, I'm Catherine btw ;)

For what it's worth, I'm planning on doing 162 + 186 + Physics 7A next semester, and have heard that that's a somewhat tight, but apparently doable workload. I'm excited for 162 and 186 though, since they seem mostly project based (hoping to finally learn something applicable for once!)
CS 188 is not redundant after 189 - they cover completely different topics. The only redundant topic would be the neural net part of 188 but that's just the last two weeks of the class.

Commenting on CS 188/DS100/EE127:

Prof. Shewchuk explicitly said CS188 is not related to his version of CS189. (current student in CS189 this semester) It's also been said that 188 is redundant after taking 189. (I don't know why but this has been said on this piazza many times) That said, my friends and roommates have told me that this course is light workload (tough exams though) and is a good pairing course if you have other heavy coursework in your semester.

Data 100 is the nuts and bolts of data science. While CS188 and CS189 may teach you the fancy/sexy modelling part of doing data science, there is a lot of data science work that is fundamentally unrelated to building fancy models. If you want to understand data science comprehensively take this class and then CS189 afterwards. 

EE 127 is useful for Prof. Shewchuk's version of 189 because almost every math heavy problem that we have done is either a linear algebra related proof (a la math 110 or 16 series) or solving a convex optimization problem, which is essentially some material from 127 from my understanding.
